TY  - JOUR
AU  - Schlafmann, Kathrin
T1  - Housing, Mortgages, and Self-Control
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa096
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 34
IS  - 5
SP  - 2648
EP  - 2687
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Using a quantitative theoretical framework this paper analyzes how problems of self-control influence housing and mortgage decisions. The results show that people with stronger problems of self-control are less likely to become homeowners, even though houses serve as commitment for saving. The paper then investigates the welfare effects of regulating mortgage products if people differ in their degree of self-control. Holding house prices fixed, higher down payment requirements and restrictions on refinancing turn out to be beneficial to people with sufficiently strong problems of self-control, even though these policies restrict access to the commitment device.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa096
ER  - 



